Brussel Antonio peeters
monsr. Ick kan mij niet genoch verwonderen dat ul al willens, sijn goederen
laet verloren gaen & ul saeke niet assisteert mons. langhter van
london sal de goederen niet begeiren, soo noch lanseer getardeert word
oock wille ick een eijnde hebbe alsoude ick selfs de goederen & stulden
in de crifie al hier consigneeren & mij voorderest expuseeren oversulxx
rade icku als vrint delayert niet langer & comt overtegens sondagh alceurd
sijnde 2 steyligh dagen dat ul niet kan verleten & brenght mede de

Brussel Stepa. Kints
monsr. De ul van 20 & 3 deser wel ontfangen wegens het carmesijen pack
laken en is noch niet te voorschijn gekomen nochte bij volnelinx nochte
emant anders oversulx soo het selve verneme sal het u wedersenden hebt
pack op stallevertreckt morgen, wegens ul deventer bay groot frisaert
referre dat aen mons. govert ververs, want hij den koop heeft helpen
maken & wet hoe het selve moet sijn, de ncke ul niet tegens de
redens iets pretendeert waer in ul voor kan dinst doen

ick hebu 2 leste brieven wel ontfangen, en daghte voor nu van amsterdam
al wol soude hebben gesteirt, maer die is mij daer wat ontvallen soo sal de naeste
weeke in baele senden bij al dien van Amsterdam geen komt, ick hebbe
het laken N.6 ontfangen maer dat scijns soo claer niet te syn gevolt als
het eerst N.1. debree leijften vallen noch wat te veel gelopt aendeynden
soo dat de leysten daer noch wel dienden wat liberder tevallen, ick wenste
wel dat ul hier woonde, want het verre aff is ende d'ongelden vallen noch
al groot: ick heb ul coleur gesien, maer de mengelinge bevalt mij niet wel
dat ul hier woonde, u scoone vader soude i konnen leeren selfs verven
gelijk hij aen matthijs peeters heeft gedaen laet de lakens die ul voor mij
maeht naer leyden gerolt worden tot naerder order a 29 sber
Leuven Joan De Goede
hebbe op 23 deser aen ul het noodigh geadviseert, wegens de witte laken

London Michiel peeters
monsr. volgens voor desen pr mijnen lesten had geadviseert soo soude de lakens
al hebben gesonden, maer u broeder en antwoort mijne brieven niet nochte
en komt niet over omonse saeke te advisteeren, waer over mij niet geno
genoegaem verwondere nademael sijn intrest daer van soo veel dependert
ende ick bereiydt ben alles te effenen, oversulx, kan ul hem daer toe niet pramen
om met mij een eijnde te maken soo magh ul afwaghten tgeene mr. slaughter
doen sal want: scoon ick ul ordre hebbe, soo nochtas moet ul broeder
daer overstaen als mede beneffens ul geinterresseirt didt dint ul voor goven
terwijlen u spoedigh antwoort verwagte blijve @ 27 ditto 1681

of waters, butt next week they are here exspected when I shall endeavour to make
the most of them in closed remitt you Â£50: on Iames Busk att 35:5: for
yds acctt. for which please to procure the needfull & note accordingly - I have
thought good to accquaint you that our flanders laces are extroard nary
cheap here that imdese you would apply yd self to itt you might make
great propress there in, & gett much mony there is sir thomas stampps tath
seen itt above 20 yeare & certainey made good conquest by them: I have
been imployee in buymp of laves ever sence I oras last in England
andam now come to aperfect understanding of that some, so that I may
vere well assure you, that no man canprovide better goods & peny wort hs

S. my last to you was on the 20: curitt. sence recd. both yd of 9 & 12 ditto I do exspect
the 6.N silver marck cloathes as soone as possible have given you breditt for my
half share in the frises & I wanshins bayes as also the bayes shipt att Hull, my
thanckes for yd providing of the pen knifes & stockings, butt you do not note their
cost the 2 bed tjkes go for ward to day to be sent you pr vere first: from
bruges itt beeng 1Â½ I seal & 1Â¼3 seal bed tijkes which will lost Â½ 3 seal
aÆ’26: - and the Â£ 2 seal Æ’14 free abourd att bruges: so plase to gied yds,
acctts creditt for the valew Æ’40:- mr furnese hath been here & hope will
be with you as soone as this, he lath leest mee order to pay about Æ’1600:-
which will be don accordingly & when I know the neett summe shall advise
you to be noted in my creditt the goods from bruges are not yett come in trim
our sale is not considerable so that I finde no neet to in order much except
what lately I wrott for, yett seeng the goods, begin to fall, hope will come
lower that when you finde the best time I might proved to provide some
parcell, so please constantely to advise how the markett doth rule for
northren goods, shall send you pattarnes to provide a bale or 2: mr. Thomas suittes
doth indifferent well butt stuck mr. parrson doth as well, & aldermanlykes
better, of which more when I see you for till that time I thnck to in order
little or name then goods & so with kinde saluto I supose the Æ’1600:-
to pay for mr. furnaise will satisfye you for this weeks remise thement

London Henry Collier
Sr. In answer to yd of 12: curitt I have sold most part of yd cottons butt cloth dothlije
by the wall, I odo not beleave that trade ever was so badd in the de countreys in the
time of wares wee hadd more mony & much more demande butt the generall
best is to be prefend the bussynes of Tft. are bpought to extreamitie, for he
is onee exceuted, so that he can betaken where they finde him butt bickely
yeasterday desired to know if I was not the mane that menaged the bussynes
& what I had to do with itt: I could him that itt was Herreyme that hath
order & power to do & leave as he shall thuck convenient & that I have onely
order to nay the charges, butt that I hoped, that m. hart opp should pay both
capitall & charges, att which he replyed that he should do itt, butt wants fime
& that bichley he him se intends to see you saddamly, exspecting Roger
Jones from Londons with whom he will come over in the meane while
paywrite yd order fully to mr. Herrince that he may shew itt TH
& that I be not suspec ted in the bustynes. the bill of LK shall be accepted
@ 27 ditto
& noted to yd order which I remaine

Sr. my last to you was on the 20: curitt sence recd. yd of 12 ditto the bedityhes
are al toghether foulded & don up in papers ready to be sent forward, yett shall
endeavour to make in each bale some duble peeces, noth how they are ordered
& shall send them you within 3 or 4 dayes, they are all pure good goods shall asso
abate what possibley I can to continew the trade my next shall as to
carly a note how to dye the salempores butt the 3 bales of lony cloth may
conce haw, so asthey are bought, I have sent you one packett of laces, the second
is one itts may which pray make the most off & Ill sendno more for my owne
itt is principally, that now you might see what I am able to do, andingloys
mee as well as others in case you finde in corridgement, of which wee will
discours more when you come over: ietrii hope N8 N. 3 ftuil
time in yd handes of which exspect yd advise & remaine
